{
  "message": "ui(welcome/slide-3): rewrite \u2014 drop pejorative tags + RaBitQ self-call-out\n\nPer user feedback ('+ pay per query / + no sharing \u2014 none of them are\nright'): the previous slide framed Pinecone/BigQuery/FAISS as\nstrawmen with editorializing '+ tags', AND listed RaBitQ\n(a Ruvector-family kernel, not a competitor) under 'Library' alongside\nFAISS \u2014 awkward call-out of our own tech.\n\nRewrite:\n  - Headline: 'Three current options. All hurt.' \u2192\n              'Three shapes today. Each has a trade-off.'\n  - Body rewritten as honest descriptions: vector DB is purpose-built\n    but means a new service + data replication; warehouse already\n    holds the data but charges per query; library is fast but\n    in-process so no shared verifiable view.\n  - Per-card text:\n      Vector DB: 'purpose-built / replicates data / cost: a new service'\n      Warehouse: 'data already there / queries hit cluster / cost: $ per query'\n      Library:   'in-process \u00b7 fast / per-agent state / cost: no shared view'\n    Drops product names (Pinecone, Weaviate, BigQuery, Snowflake,\n    FAISS, RaBitQ) \u2014 they made the slide read like a hit-piece on\n    specific competitors. The shapes are what matter.\n  - Footer: 'none of them are right for AI agents' \u2192\n            'none of them give agents a shared, verifiable middle layer'\n    states the actual missing thing rather than dismissing alternatives.",
  "files": [
